Sampling Methods


Yuji Saikai
ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au
School of Mathematics and Statistics
The University of Melbourne

These notes are based on Chapter 2.7 of Kroese, D. P., & Chan, J. C. (2014). Statistical modeling and computation. New York: Springer.

Introduction

To use Monte Carlo methods, first we specify random variables and then take samples from them. In Monte Carlo integration, we mostly use only uniform and exponential distributions, for which we can simply call R built-in samplers (runif or rexp). In the last example, however, we sample from the non-standard distribution using one of the methods covered in these notes.

In general, sampling can be quite challenging as our models become complex. For example, in Bayesian statistics, we are interested in the posterior mean \[\mathbb{E}[\theta|\mathbf{x}] = \int_\theta \theta f(\theta|\mathbf{x})d\theta\] and the predictive distribution \[f(\tilde{x}|\mathbf{x}) = \int_\theta f(\tilde{x}|\theta,\mathbf{x})f(\theta|\mathbf{x})d\theta\] with respect to the posterior PDF \[f(\theta|\mathbf{x}) = \frac{f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)f(\theta)}{\int_\theta f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)f(\theta)d\theta}.\]

In many practical applications, \(\theta\) is multi-dimensional and MC integration is one of the common approaches to computing these integrals. However, as you can imagine by noticing the product and division involved in the formula, posterior PDFs can easily become unwieldy. Thus, we need methods to sample from non-standard and often unwieldy PDFs.

We cover three sampling methods in ascending order of sophistication:

  • Inverse transform method
  • Rejection sampling
  • Markov chain Monte Carlo (in separate notes)

Inverse transform method

The method is applicable only to cases in which we can invert CDFs. If applicable, it is fast and reliable.

Invertible CDFs

To illustrate the idea, consider a case where \(F\) as the CDF for \(X\) is invertible (e.g., \(X\sim \text{N}(0,1)\)). Then, given \(U\sim \text{U}(0,1)\), the CDF for a transformed random variable \(Y=F^{-1}(U)\) turns out to be the same CDF for \(X\). To see this, for arbitrary \(y\in\mathbb{R}\),

\[\begin{align} P(Y\leq y) &= P(F^{-1}(U)\leq y)\\ &= P(U\leq F(y))\\ &= F(y)\\ &= P(X\leq y) \end{align}\]

which implies that \(X\) and \(Y\) share the same CDF.

f <- function(x) 1/(1+exp(-(x-2)))

par(mar=c(2,.5,1,.5))
curve(1/(1+exp(-(x-2))), from=-2, to=7, lwd=1.5, axes=FALSE, ann=FALSE)
axis(side=1, at=c(-4,0,2.5,8), labels=c("","0","X",""))
abline(v=0)
lines(c(0,7), c(1,1), lty=3)
arrows(0, f(2.5), 2.5, f(2.5),length=.1,angle=20)
arrows(2.5, f(2.5), 2.5, -.01,length=.1,angle=20)
text(0, f(2.5), "U", pos=2)
text(0, 1, "1", pos=2)

Since the CDF completely characterise the random variable, the identical CDF between \(X\) and \(Y\) means that, to sample from \(X\), we may sample from \(Y\). Given the knowledge of \(F^{-1}\), it is easy to sample from \(Y\):

  1. sample \(u\) from \(U[0,1]\), and
  2. transform \(u\) to get a sample \(y=F^{-1}(u)\) from \(Y\).

Note that the definition \(Y=F^{-1}(U)\) implies \(U=F(Y)\). Since \(X\) and \(Y\) have the same distribution and \(X\) is an arbitrary continuous random variable, we have \(U=F(X)\) if we transform an arbitrary \(X\) using its CDF, we have a random variable of \(U(0,1)\).

Invertible CDFs over the supports

CDFs for many random variables are technically not invertible. Remember the definition of a random variable a function whose co-domain is \(\mathbb{R}\) and the domain of \(F\) is \(\mathbb{R}\). Thus, to be invertible, \(F\) must be strictly increasing over \(\mathbb{R}\). Equivalently, the support of \(X\) must be \(\mathbb{R}\). This condition excludes many random variables including exp(\(\lambda\)) and gamma(\(m,\lambda\)) whose support are only the half real line.

However, we are interested in samples from the support \(\mathcal{S}\) for \(X\). So, we may just define \(G\) on \(\mathcal{S}\) such that \(G(x)=F(x)\) for all \(x\in\mathcal{S}\). Then, \(G\) is invertible and we can generate a sample \(G^{-1}(u)\) for \(X\).

CDFs for discretes

When \(X\) is discrete, \(F\) is a step function as below.

To deal with a more general case, we may use the following \(H^{-1}:(0,1)\to\mathbb{R}\) to generate a sample \(H^{-1}(u)\) for \(X\): \[ H^{-1}: u \mapsto \inf\{x : F(x)\geq u\}.\]

n.b.\(H^{-1}\) is just a notation and does not imply anything about another function \(H\).

Notice that \(H^{-1}\) is a generalisation of \(F^{-1}\) or \(G^{-1}\), and it also works in those special cases. Of course, having the exact mathematical definition per se does not mean it is easy to use in practice; instead, given \(u\), we must search for \(x\) such that \(\min\{x : F(x)\geq u\}\), which may not be easy. For \(X\) with a finite support, we can use R built-in function sample(x, prob, ...) by passing the desired PMF to prob. But, it is impractical if the support contains so many elements that causes numerical issues (e.g., prob consists of too small numbers).

Example

Lets generate samples from \(\text{exp}(1)\) whose CDF is \(F(x)=1-e^{-x}\) for \(x\geq0\) and \(0\) otherwise. Solving the following \[\begin{alignat}{2} && u &= 1-e^{-x}\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & x &= -\log(1-u)\\ \end{alignat}\] we find \(G^{-1}(u) = -\log(1-u)\). Below is a histogram together with the PDF of \(\text{exp}(1)\).

n <- 1e6
u <- runif(n)
x_exp <- -log(u) # U and 1-U have the same distribution
x <- x_exp[x_exp<6] # truncated for visualisation
hist(x, seq(0, 6, .1), freq=F, ylim=c(0,1), main="PDF for exp(1)")
curve(exp(-x), from=0, lwd=2, add=T)

\(U_1\sim\text{U}(0,1)\) and \(U_2=1-U_1\) have the same probability distribution. For \(x\in\mathbb{R}\), \[ P(U_2\leq x) = P(1-U_1\leq x) = P(U_1\geq 1-x) = 1 - (1-x) = x = P(U_1\leq x). \]

We use the method in the importance sampling to sample from the PDF \(f(x) = 0.5x^{-0.5}\).

Rejection sampling

Even when the inverse of \(F\) exists, inverting \(F\) is often analytically impossible or numerically too expensive (i.e., root finding at every evaluation of \(F^{-1}(u)\)). In these cases, we may try the rejection sampling. The rejection sampling is based on the following intuition.

Obtain a random sample \((x,y)\) using uniform sampling from the region formed by the \(x\)-axis and the density curve of \(X\). Then, keep \(x\) as a sample from \(X\).

The beauty of this method is that we need not directly sample from the target PDF, but only uniformly sample from the region under the graph of the target PDF.

Recall that, by uniform sampling from set \(A\subset\mathbb{R}^d\), we mean sampling from the joint PDF \(f(x) = \mathbb{1}_A(x)/|A|\) where \(|A|\) is the Lebesgue measure.

How can we obtain random samples uniformly taken from that region? A trick is to find another PDF \(g\) that satisfies the following conditions:

  • It is easy to sample from.
  • There exists a constant \(C>0\) such that \(Cg(x)\geq f(x)\) for all \(x\in\mathbb{R}\).

Given the envelope PDF \(g\), here is the algorithm to collect uniform samples from the region.

  1. Sample \(x\) from \(g\).
  2. Sample \(y\) from \(\text{U}(0, Cg(x))\).
  3. Keep \((x,y)\) as a sample if \(0<y\leq f(x)\); otherwise reject it.

The claim is intuitive but may not be obvious. So, two key facts are stated as lemmas below.

Target \(f\) need not be normalised because \(C\) can absorb the normalisation constant of \(f\). This is very convenient in practice. For example, the denominator \(\int f(\mathbf{x}|\theta)f(\theta)d\theta\) in a posterior PDF may be difficult to compute.

Example

Lets generate samples from \(X\sim \text{N}(0,1)\). There are two observations to make. Since the PDF is symmetric about \(0\), once we generate positive samples, we can randomly flip their signs to generate negative samples. The PDF for the positive half can be derived by re-normalising the original PDF: \[ f(x) = \begin{cases} \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}}e^{-x^2/2} & x\geq0\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} . \]

The normalisation constant \(\kappa = \sqrt{2/\pi}\) is obtained by the following \[\begin{align} 1 &= \int_0^\infty \kappa e^{-x^2/2}dx\\ &= \kappa\int_0^\infty e^{-x^2/2}dx\\ &= \kappa\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2}}. \end{align}\] The last equality is due to the right half of the standard normal PDF, \[\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-x^2/2}dx = \frac{1}{2}.\]

Next, notice that we can bound the above \(f\) by \(Cg(x)\) where \(g\) is the PDF for \(\text{exp}(1)\) and \(C=\sqrt{2e/\pi}\).

Notice \(1 = {\operatorname{argmax}} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\) and \(C = \frac{f(1)}{g(1)}\).

curve(sqrt(2*exp(1)/pi)*exp(-x), from=0, to=4, ylab="f(x)", lty=3)
curve(sqrt(2/pi)*exp(-x^2/2), from=0, to=4, add=TRUE)
title(bquote(f(x) ~ "bounded by" ~ Ce^-x))
legend(2.9, 1.2, lty=c(1,3),
       legend=c("Half normal", expression(Ce^-x)))

Here is a result.

half.normal <- function(x) sqrt(2/pi)*exp(-x^2/2)
C <- sqrt(2*exp(1)/pi)

y <- runif(length(x_exp))*C*exp(-x_exp) # Reuse x_exp from exp(1)
x_pos <- x_exp[y <= half.normal(x_exp)] # Keep those under the target PDF
ind <- 1:floor(length(x_pos)/2) # Half sample for negative values
x_neg <- -x_pos[ind]
x_pos <- x_pos[-ind]
x <- c(x_neg[x_neg>-4], x_pos[x_pos<4]) # truncate for visualisation
res <- hist(x, 100, freq=F, ylab="f(x)", xlim=c(-4,4), main="PDF for N(0,1)")
curve(max(res$density)*exp(-x^2/2), lwd=2, add=T)

Lemma 1

A uniform sample \((x,y)\) from the region under the curve \(y=Cg(x)\) can be obtained by first sampling \(x\) from the PDF \(g\) and then sampling \(y\) from \(\text{U}(0,Cg(x))\) given \(x\).

Let \(h\) be the conditional PDF for \(Y|X=x\) following \(\text{U}(0,Cg(x))\): \[ h(y|x) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{Cg(x)} & y\in[0,Cg(x)]\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} . \] Then, observe the following joint PDF for \((x,y)\): \[\begin{align} f(x,y) &= h(y|x)g(x)\\ &= \frac{1}{Cg(x)}g(x)\\ &= \frac{1}{C}, \end{align}\] which implies the uniform joint distribution.

Lemma 2

Let \(A,B\subset\mathbb{R}^2\) such that \(A\subseteq B\). If \(\{X_n\} = X_1,X_2,\dots\) is an IID sequence obtained by uniform sampling from \(B\). Then, a subsequence \(\{X_{n_k}\} = X_{n_1},X_{n_2},\dots\) such that \(X_{n_k}\in A\) for all \(k\geq1\) is an IID sequence obtained by uniform sampling from \(A\).

When you watch the animation in Estimating \(\pi\), dont you think dots look uniformly distributed inside the quarter disk?

First, consider the probability that \(X\) falls inside a small region \(\Delta A\subset A\). \[\begin{align} P(X\in \Delta A |X\in A) &= \frac{P(X\in(\Delta A\cap A))}{P(X\in A)}\\ &= \frac{P(X\in \Delta A)}{P(X\in A)}\\ &= \frac{\int_{\Delta A}f(x)dx}{\int_{A}f(x)dx} \end{align}\]

Then, the conditional density at \(x\in \Delta A\) given \(X\in A\) is: \[\begin{align} f(x|X\in A) &= \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \frac{P(X\in \Delta A | X\in A)}{|\Delta A|}\\ &= \frac{1}{\int_{A}f(x)dx} \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0}\frac{\int_{\Delta A}f(x)dx}{|\Delta A|}\\ &= \frac{f(x)}{\int_{A}f(x)dx} \end{align}\] To see why the limit, remember the definition of PDF, which can be adapted to the following: \[ P_{X|A}(\Delta A) = \int_{\Delta A}dP_{X|A} = \int_{\Delta A}f(x|X\in A)dx. \] Since it holds for every \(\Delta A \subset A\), by taking a small leap of faith, we see it also hold in the limit: \[ \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} P_{X|A}(\Delta A) = \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \int_{\Delta A}f(x|X\in A)dx. \] Now, by the definition of CDF, \[ \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} P_{X|A}(\Delta A) = \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \Delta F_{X|A}(x). \] Consequently, by the fundamental theorem of calculus, \[ \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \int_{\Delta A}f(x|X\in A)dx = \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \Delta F_{X|A}(x) \] implies \[\begin{align} f(x|X\in A) &= \frac{dF_{X|A}(x)}{dx}\\ &= \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \frac{\Delta F_{X|A}(x)}{|\Delta A|}\\ &= \lim_{|\Delta A|\to 0} \frac{P(X\in \Delta A | X\in A)}{|\Delta A|}. \end{align}\]

The exposition would be simpler and require no leap of faith with measure theaory (c.f., absolute continuity and the Radon-Nikodym derivative).

An implication is that, if \(X\) is uniformly distributed over \(B\), \[\begin{align} f(x|X\in A) &= \frac{\frac{1}{|B|}}{\frac{|A|}{|B|}}\\ &= \frac{1}{|A|}\\ \end{align}\]

which is a constant and integrates to \(1\) over \(A\). Hence, a subset of uniform samples from \(B\) that also belong to \(A\) are indeed uniformly distributed over \(A\).
